<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-536-634  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 536 634.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEE Proceedings Part E Computers and Digital Techniques  July 1989v136 n4 p225(9).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>TOMP project. (Torino multiprocessor research project)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Del Corso, D.; Civera, P.; Gregoretti, F.; Maddaleno, F.; Conte,G.; Zamboni, M.; Pasero, E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The main objective of the TOMP (Torino multiprocessor) project wasthe development of a frame under which a wide variety of multipleprocessor systems could be sized up, designed, and built.andP;  Theframe was not conceived for a specific purpose, the basic goalbeing to cover a wide area of applications, where the keyparameters were the relevance of the distribution of thefunctions, and the computational needs required by real-timeapplications.andP;  The paper presents the methodologies usedthroughout the project, describing the development and the use ofdescription and performance evaluation techniques, the choices atthe architectural level, the design of a high-performancebackplane bus, the basic software developed to make the hardwareoperational, and the results of some experiments on parallelprogramming.andP;  (Reprinted by permission of the publisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Circuit DesignMultiprocessingSystem DesignProcessor ArchitectureApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Description techniques. (table)Description of Cm multiprocessor system with PMS and MSBInotations. (chart)Bus-based multiprocessor architectures with shared memory. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>